SIMPLE: torment
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Torment
<hw>Tor"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>torment</ets>, F. <ets>tourment</ets>, fr. L. <ets>tormentum</ets>
an engine for hurling missiles, an instrument of torture, a rack,
torture, fr. <ets>torquere</ets> to turn, to twist, hurl. See
<er>Turture</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mil. Antiq.)</fld> <def>An
engine for casting stones.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir T.
Elyot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Extreme pain; anguish; torture; the utmost degree of
misery, either of body or mind.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The more I see⟦br⟧
Pleasures about me, so much more I feel⟦br⟧
<qex>Torment</qex> within me.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which gives pain, vexation, or
misery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They brought unto him all sick people that were taken with divers
diseases and <qex>torments</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. iv.
24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Torment</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Torment
<hw>Tor*ment"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>tormented</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>tormenting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF.
<ets>tormenter</ets>, F. <ets>tourmenter</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To put to extreme pain or anguish; to inflict excruciating misery
upon, either of body or mind; to torture.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ Art thou come
hither to <xex>torment</xex> us before our time? ⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Matt.
viii. 29.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pain; to distress; to afflict.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lord, my servant lieth at home sick of the palsy, grievously
<qex>tormented</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. viii. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To tease; to vex; to harass; <as>as, to be
<ex>tormented</ex> with importunities, or with petty
annoyances</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To put into great agitation.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧[They], soaring on main wing, <xex>tormented</xex> all the
air.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tormenter</ent>⟦br⟧
